Adult male.description: Adult male Baltimore Orioles are bright orange instead of a rich chestnut color like adult male Orchard Orioles.

Adult female.description: Adult female Baltimore Orioles are more orange on the breast and tail, and less greenish yellow than female Orchard Orioles.

Female.description: Female Bullock's Orioles have a whiter belly and tend to be more orangish than female Orchard Orioles which are more greenish yellow overall and have a greenish yellow belly.

Female and immature male Hooded Orioles are best distinguished by shape: they are slightly larger, with a longer tail and a longer, distinctly curved bill compared to Orchard Orioles. Hooded also have thinner wingbars.
Female and nonbreeding male Scarlet Tanagers are chunkier birds with a much heavier bill and blackish wings without wingbars unlike female Orchard Orioles which have wingbars.

Male.description: Scott's Orioles of the Southwest and Mexico have little range overlap with Orchard Oriole. Scott's is larger and longer-tailed with yellow instead of chestnut underparts.

Adult female.description: Dull warblers such as Pine Warblers can look like female Orchard Orioles, but they are smaller, with more compact proportions and a shorter, less pointed bill.

Breeding female.description: American Goldfinches are much smaller, with shorter proportions and a smaller, thicker bill compared to female Orchard Orioles.

Female.description: Western Tanagers have thicker and stubbier bills than Orchard Orioles.
